    "summarizer": {
      "general_reader_takeaway": "This paper studies how a cloud of ultralight scalar dark matter around a massive black hole changes the gravitational wave signals produced when a small compact object spirals inward \u2014 a system called an extreme-mass-ratio inspiral (EMRI), a key target for the planned LISA space detector. The paper argues that a previously uncomputed gravitational effect \u2014 the \"polar\" metric sector coupling to the scalar cloud \u2014 can actually dominate all other dark-matter-induced corrections to the waves in parts of the relevant parameter range. The review board found this a timely and credible gap-filling contribution, though the results are demonstrated for an idealized spherical, non-spinning setup with an optimistic cloud mass, and the detectability implications for realistic superradiant clouds around spinning black holes require further work.",
      "reviewer": "claude",
      "technical_takeaway": "The paper presents the first fully coupled computation of the polar gravitational-wave flux sector for circular EMRIs in a spherically symmetric scalar cloud on a Schwarzschild background, extending the Zerilli formalism to a six-dimensional coupled scalar-metric perturbation system. The paper claims that polar metric backreaction corrections can dominate axial and scalar dissipative channels for scalar field masses \u03bcM \u2272 0.2 at small separations, and that conservative geodesic corrections from cloud backreaction on the metric can further dominate total waveform dephasing. Two analytic limits are presented: a gravitational redshift at small separation/low cloud compactness, and a mass shift at large separation/high compactness. Numerical validation uses the Black Hole Perturbation Toolkit for vacuum benchmarks and reproduces prior scalar flux results. An extrapolation procedure removes unphysical O(\u03b1\u00b2) terms arising from the perturbative expansion in scalar field amplitude."
    }
